<RetrofittedStudentLesson paperSize="A4" language="English" version="2.27.0">
  <RSLIdeaSection title="Key features of quadratic functions" id="id-for-idea">
    <RSLIdeaTheory>
      <Text>
        When a quadratic function is sketched on a Cartesian plane, it is called
        a <RSLGlossaryTerm>parabola</RSLGlossaryTerm>.
      </Text>
      <Text>
        The most simple quadratic function is <Latex expression="y=x^2" />. The
        table shows the corresponding -values for values of between -4 and 4.
      </Text>
      <TabularData
        rowTitles={['x', 'y']}
        rowTitlesAs="latex"
        rowData={[
          ['-4', '-3', '-2', '-1', '0', '1', '2', '3', '4'],
          ['16', '9', '4', '1', '0', '1', '4', '9', '16'],
        ]}
        rowDataAs="latex"
      />
      <Text>
        Using the table, the graph of <Latex expression="y=x^2" /> can be
        sketched on a Cartesian plane.
      </Text>
      <CartesianPlane
        width={596}
        height={260}
        xAxis={{
          min: -8,
          max: 8,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 1,
          intervalSubdivisions: 2,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'improperFraction',
          label: 'x',
        }}
        yAxis={{
          min: -4,
          max: 18,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 2,
          intervalSubdivisions: 4,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'y',
        }}
      >
        <FunctionPlot f={(x) => x ** 2} />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => -3}
          domain={[-8.5, -8.5]}
          labelLatex="\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad Turning point(0,0)"
        />
        <Vector p1={[1, -2.5]} p2={[0, 0]} color="pickledBluewood" />
        <Point x={0} y={0} color="mountainMeadow" />
        <Point x={-1} y={1} />
        <Point x={-2} y={4} />
        <Point x={-3} y={9} />
        <Point x={-4} y={16} />
        <Point x={1} y={1} />
        <Point x={2} y={4} />
        <Point x={3} y={9} />
        <Point x={4} y={16} />
      </CartesianPlane>
      <Text>
        The point is called the <RSLGlossaryTerm>turning point</RSLGlossaryTerm> of the graph. In this case,
        turning point is also the <Latex expression="x" />
        -intercept and the <Latex expression="y" />
        -intercept of the graph.
      </Text>
      <Text>A summary of the features of the basic parabola:</Text>
      <List type="bullet">
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          <Latex expression="y=-x^2" /> is a reflection of{' '}
          <Latex expression="y=x^2" /> across the x-axis
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          Graphs with a positive coefficient of <Latex expression="x" /> are <RSLGlossaryTerm>concave up</RSLGlossaryTerm>.
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          Graphs with a positive coefficient of <Latex expression="x" /> are <RSLGlossaryTerm>concave down</RSLGlossaryTerm>.
        </ListItem>
      </List>
      <Text>
        The <Latex expression="x" />
        -intercepts are where the parabola corsses the <Latex expression="x" />-
        axis. This occurs when <Latex expression="y=0" />.
      </Text>
      <Text>
        The <Latex expression="y" />
        -intercepts are where the parabola corsses the <Latex expression="y" />-
        axis. This occurs when <Latex expression="x=0" />.
      </Text>
      <CartesianPlane
        width={260}
        height={260}
        xAxis={{
          min: -20,
          max: 20,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 5,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'improperFraction',
          label: 'x',
        }}
        yAxis={{
          min: -20,
          max: 20,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 5,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'y',
        }}
      >
        <FunctionPlot f={(x) => (x - 3) ** 2 - 18} />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => 10}
          domain={[-22, -22]}
          labelLatex="x-intercepts"
        />
        <Vector p1={[-5, 10]} p2={[-1.3, 0.6]} color="pickledBluewood" />
        <Vector p1={[-5, 10]} p2={[7.3, 0.6]} color="pickledBluewood" />
        <Point x={-1.3} y={0} color="lochmara" />
        <Point x={0} y={-7} color="lochmara" />
        <Point x={7.3} y={0} color="lochmara" />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => -7}
          domain={[-28, -28]}
          labelLatex="\qquad \qquad y-intercept"
        />
      </CartesianPlane>
      <Text>
        Parabolas will always have exactly one <Latex expression="y" />
        -intercept. However, they can have zero, one or two{' '}
        <Latex expression="x" />
        -intercepts (as seen in the diagram). The <Latex expression="x" />
        -intercepts are also known as the roots or solutions to the function.
      </Text>
      <CartesianPlane
        width={260}
        height={260}
        xAxis={{
          min: -0.5,
          max: 0.5,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 1,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'x',
        }}
        yAxis={{
          min: -0.5,
          max: 1,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 1,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'y',
        }}
      >
        <FunctionPlot f={(x) => (x + 0.5) ** 2 + 0.35} />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => -0.1}
          domain={[-2, -2]}
          labelLatex="\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \quad No   Solution"
        />
      </CartesianPlane>
      <Text>
        Turning points can show the minimum or maximum values, and are also
        referred to as the <RSLGlossaryTerm>vertex</RSLGlossaryTerm>.
      </Text>
      <RSLAnnotatedFigure>
      <CartesianPlane
        width={260}
        height={260}
        xAxis={{
          min: -20,
          max: 20,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 5,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'improperFraction',
          label: 'x',
        }}
        yAxis={{
          min: -20,
          max: 20,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 5,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'y',
        }}
      >
        <FunctionPlot f={(x) => (x - 10) ** 2 - 15} />
        <Point x={10} y={-15} color="lochmara" />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => -17}
          domain={[-27, -27]}
          labelLatex="\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \enspace \text{Minimum Value}"
        />
      </CartesianPlane>
       <RSLFigureAnnotation>
          <Text>
            Parabolas that are concave up have a <RSLGlossaryTerm>minimum</RSLGlossaryTerm> value.
          </Text>
        </RSLFigureAnnotation>
      </RSLAnnotatedFigure>
      <RSLAnnotatedFigure>
      <CartesianPlane
        width={260}
        height={260}
        xAxis={{
          min: -20,
          max: 20,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 5,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'improperFraction',
          label: 'x',
        }}
        yAxis={{
          min: -20,
          max: 20,
          scale: 1,
          interval: 5,
          intervalSubdivisions: 1,
          unit: '',
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'y',
        }}
      >
        <FunctionPlot f={(x) => 15 - (x + 10) ** 2} />
        <Point x={-10} y={15} color="lochmara" />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => 17}
          domain={[-28, -28]}
          labelLatex="\qquad \enspace \text{Maximum Value}"
        />
      </CartesianPlane>
      <RSLFigureAnnotation>
          <Text>
            Parabolas that are concave down have a <RSLGlossaryTerm>maximum</RSLGlossaryTerm> value.
          </Text>
        </RSLFigureAnnotation>
      </RSLAnnotatedFigure>
      <Text>
        Maximum and minimum values occur on a parabola's <RSLGlossaryTerm>axis of symmetry</RSLGlossaryTerm>. This
        is the vertical line that evenly divides a parabola into two halves. A
        quadratic in the general form <Latex expression="y=ax^2+bx+c" /> will
        have the axis of symmetry at:
      </Text>
      <AlgebraicWorking>
        <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
          <AlgebraicWorkingStatement
            lhs="x"
            relation="="
            rhs="\dfrac{-b}{2a}"
          />
        </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
      </AlgebraicWorking>
    </RSLIdeaTheory>

