    <RSLIdeaSummary>
      <Text>A parabola hase these key features:</Text>
      <List type="bullet">
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          <RSLGlossaryTerm>Maximum</RSLGlossaryTerm> and <RSLGlossaryTerm>minimum </RSLGlossaryTerm>values
          <Text>
            {' '}
            The maximum or minimum value, also known as the <RSLGlossaryTerm>turning point</RSLGlossaryTerm>, is
            found at the <RSLGlossaryTerm>vertex</RSLGlossaryTerm> of the parabola.
          </Text>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          <Latex expression="y=-x^2" /> is a reflection of{' '}
          <Latex expression="y=x^2" /> across the x-axis.
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          Graphs with a positive coefficient of <Latex expression="x" /> are <RSLGlossaryTerm>concave up</RSLGlossaryTerm>.
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          {' '}
          Graphs with a positive coefficient of <Latex expression="x" /> are <RSLGlossaryTerm>concave down</RSLGlossaryTerm>.
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          Intercepts
          <Text>
            The <Latex expression="x" />
            -intercepts are where the parabola crosses the{' '}
            <Latex expression="x" />
            -axis. This occurs when <Latex expression="y=0" />. The{' '}
            <Latex expression="y" />
            -intercept is where the parabola crosses the{' '}
            <Latex expression="y" />
            -axis This occurs when <Latex expression="x=0" />.
          </Text>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
          Axis of Symmetry
          <Text>
            For a quadtric in general form, <Latex expression="y=ax^2+bx+c" />,
            the <RSLGlossaryTerm>axis of symmetry</RSLGlossaryTerm> is at{' '}
          </Text>
          <Text>
            <Latex expression="x =\dfrac{-b}{2a}" />.
          </Text>
        </ListItem>
      </List>
    </RSLIdeaSummary>
  </RSLIdeaSection>
  <RSLIdeaSection title="Graph of quadratics using technology" id="idea">
    <RSLIdeaTheory>
      <Text>
        Technology can be used to graph and identify key features of a quadratic
        function. To determine an appropriate view window, we may need to use
        our knowledge of the graph or calculate the location of some key
        features.
      </Text>
    </RSLIdeaTheory>
    <RSLIdeaWorkedQuestions>
      <RSLWorkedQuestion>
        <RSLQuestionStatement>
          <Text>
            Consider the equation <Latex expression="y=-5x^2 -80x-195" />
          </Text>
        </RSLQuestionStatement>
        <RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
          <RSLSubquestionStatement>
            <Text>
              State the coordinates of <Latex expression="y" />
              -intercepts.
            </Text>
          </RSLSubquestionStatement>
          <RSLCreateAStrategy>
            <Text>
              Let <Latex expression="x=0" /> and determine{' '}
              <Latex expression="y" />.
            </Text>
          </RSLCreateAStrategy>
          <RSLApplyTheIdea>
            <AlgebraicWorking>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement
                  lhs="y"
                  relation="="
                  rhs="-5(0)2-80(0)-195"
                />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Substitute <Latex expression="x=0" /> into the equation
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement relation="=" rhs="-195" />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Evaluate
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
            </AlgebraicWorking>
            <Text>
              The <Latex expression="y" />
              -intercepts is <Latex expression="(0,-195)" />.
            </Text>
          </RSLApplyTheIdea>
        </RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
        <RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
          <RSLSubquestionStatement>
            <Text>State the coordinates of the turning point.</Text>
          </RSLSubquestionStatement>
          <RSLCreateAStrategy>
            <Text>Use <Latex expression="x=-b/2a" /> to determine the <Latex expression="x" />-value of the turning point. Then find the <Latex expression="y" />-value of the turning point.</Text>
          </RSLCreateAStrategy>
          <RSLApplyTheIdea>
            <Text>From the general form <Latex expression="y=ax^2+bx+c" />, the values of <Latex expression="a,b" /> and <Latex expression="c" /> are <Latex expression="a=-5, b=-80, c=-195" />.</Text>
            <AlgebraicWorking>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement
                  lhs="x"
                  relation="="
                  rhs="\dfrac{-b}{2a}"
                />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Write the formula
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement relation="=" rhs="\dfrac{-(-80)}{2(-5)}" />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Substitute <Latex expression="a=-5" /> and <Latex expression="b=-80" />
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement relation="=" rhs="-8" />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                 Evaluate
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement lhs="y"relation="=" rhs="-5(-8)^2-80(-8)-195" />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Substitute <Latex expression="x=-8" />
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
              <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement relation="=" rhs="-5(64)+640-195" />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Use order of operations
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingRow>
                <AlgebraicWorkingStatement relation="=" rhs="125" />
                <AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
                  Evaluate
                </AlgebraicWorkingExplanation>
              </AlgebraicWorkingRow>
            </AlgebraicWorking>
            <Text>The turning point is at <Latex expression="(-8, 125)" />.</Text>
          </RSLApplyTheIdea>
        </RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
        <RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
          <RSLSubquestionStatement>
            <Text>Sketch the graph of the equation on a Cartesian plane, labelling coordinates of the turning point and axis intercepts.</Text>
          </RSLSubquestionStatement>
          <RSLCreateAStrategy>
            <Text>Use a graphing calculator to graph <Latex expression="y=-5x^2-80x-195" />. An appropriate window must be used to check all key features: <Latex expression="x" />-intercepts, <Latex expression="y" />-intercepts and the turning point.</Text>
          </RSLCreateAStrategy>
          <RSLApplyTheIdea>
            <CartesianPlane
        width={260}
        height={260}
        xAxis={{
          min: -15,
          max: 3,
          scale: 1,
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'x',
        }}
        yAxis={{
          min: -200,
          max: 125,
          scale: 1,
          numberFormat: 'decimal',
          label: 'y',
        }}
      >
        <FunctionPlot f={(x) => (x + 0.5) ** 2 + 0.35} />
        <FunctionPlot
          f={(x) => -0.1}
          domain={[-2, -2]}
          labelLatex="\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \quad No   Solution"
        />
      </CartesianPlane>
          </RSLApplyTheIdea>
        </RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
        <RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
          <RSLSubquestionStatement>
            <Text>State the values of <Latex expression="x" /> for which the graph is decreasing.</Text>
          </RSLSubquestionStatement>
          <RSLCreateAStrategy>
            <Text>Use the graph sketched in part (c). Reading the graph from left to right, identify the parts of the graph that are going downwards.</Text>
          </RSLCreateAStrategy>
          <RSLApplyTheIdea>
            <Text>Since the turning point is at <Latex expression="(-8, 125)" />, everything on the right side of the turning point is decreasing when <Latex expression="x > -8" />.</Text>
          </RSLApplyTheIdea>
        </RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
        <RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
          <RSLSubquestionStatement>
            <Text>State the values of <Latex expression="x" /> for which the graph is increasing.</Text>
          </RSLSubquestionStatement>
          <RSLCreateAStrategy>
            <Text>Use the graph sketched in part (c). Reading the graph from left to right, identify the parts of the graph that are going upwards.</Text>
          </RSLCreateAStrategy>
          <RSLApplyTheIdea>
            <Text>Since the turning point is at <Latex expression="(-8, 125)" />, everything on the left side of the turning point is increasing when <Latex expression="x < -8" />.</Text>
          </RSLApplyTheIdea>
        </RSLWorkedQuestionPart>
      </RSLWorkedQuestion>
    </RSLIdeaWorkedQuestions>

